Oh no, apparently not. The creature growled only and tried to fly directly at Thassalin. Luckily, Thassalin, despite his size, was agile enough and dodged out of the way, but Nyssi let out a scream as she almost lost her balance on Thassalin's smooth scales.
“HOW CAN WE KILL IT?”, screamed Nyssi.
“AIM AT ITS HEADS!”
“THIS WILL BE DIFFICULT!”
Thassalin hissed and then drew a circle, closer to the mountain that he called his home. The dark beast followed, but became slightly panicked when hit from behind by a fire beam. It hadn't realized it was no longer alone. It became even more panicked when Thassalin slowed down and then threw his tail against its head, diverting it from its course.
Growling and hissing, it flew upwards and spat into the air. Everything suddenly became dark, as if the monster was sucking in the light from the sky and replacing it with a cloud of eternal night.
As soon as he could no longer see, Thassalin tried to retreat. He felt himself scraping along the treetops before he finally stumbled into a clearing. The beast seemed to know exactly where he had fallen, and it shot straight for him, dragging the black cloud with it.
“Kayel!” Tenuk shouted, as he slid out of the cloud and began to circle in the darkness below, searching for Nyssi and Thassalin. “What are we supposed to do now? Kayel…? Kayel, where are you?”
Down below, Nyssi struggled to her feet. She was sure she had broken something, but her strange, supernatural healing powers were already taking effect. Unfortunately, that didn't apply to Thassalin. He leaned exhausted against the only tree that hadn't collapsed under his weight. Nyssi made an effort to get closer to Thassalin, but she could hardly see two meters in front of her. Everything was pitch black and shrouded in eerie shadows. And in that darkness, something was screaming and shrieking.
A terrifying, armored tail crashed down beside Nyssi, sending her tumbling to the ground. But she realized that the tail was just wildly thrashing about and not specifically trying to hit her. The beast, or what little Nyssi could see and hear of it, growled and swiped at the shadows it had created. Something shot through the darkness, struck the monster, and confused it.
Suddenly, a rifle shot cracked through the fog, and the monster fell silent, collapsed on the ground, and remained motionless. The darkness around it dissipated, and they saw what had happened: Kayel stood on the beast, holding his rifle heavily.
“That was probably... The wildest Shadow Leap I've ever made... Thanto kat'olon...”, Kabel gasped for air. His eyes glowed almost black, and a dark energy swirled around his body. But while he was still speaking, the color returned to his armor, and his eyes regained their normal yellow color.
It took a moment for Nyssi to understand what had happened. They had all known that Kayel possessed these strange shadow powers. He rarely used them, because most people found them unsettling and quite intimidating. But Nyssi hadn't known that Kayel could use these powers in any type of darkness. And the way Kayel was behaving, he seemed to be quite surprised too.
“Are you okay?”, Nyssi burst out.
“Yes, I'm fine. I've killed something, I'll be okay in a moment.” Kayel examined his work, while Tenuk flew down, landed beside him, and regained its normal Spast-form.
Now that the beast wasn't moving anymore, they could see what it was. Its skin was raven-black and slimy, but the slime stayed attached to its body. It had four wings and four limbs, all ending in long, thin claws, and two straight horns protruded from its skull.
Before Tenuk and Kayel could ask what the hell they had right in front of them, something screamed and jumped out of a nearby bush. However, it didn't make it to them because a familiar vehicle crashed into its side and caused the monster to slide to a stop in front of Nyssis' feet. Nyssi didn't want to take any risks. She grabbed her shotgun, fired without thinking at its skull, and the creature died right there.
“Oops…”, muttered Retvik from the driver's seat before he shut off the engine unsteadily and stepped out of the truck. “Uh, that wasn't exactly intentional. Are you all okay?”
“You missed the whole action”, scolded Tenuk. “Where were you?”
“You just left me standing there. I came as fast as I could…”, sighed Retvik. “May I ask what these terrifying creatures are?”
Retvik's question was fortunately answered by Thassalin, who had picked himself up again. He was covered in cuts and scratches and seemed a bit dazed, but not too seriously hurt.
“YOU KILLED THE CORRUPTED ONES! THE INFECTED MONSTERS. BEINGS THAT WENT ON, AS THE CORRUPTION ATTACKED YOUR GODS."
“You mean that terrible god-monster being that we… helped to kill?”, stuttered Tenuk.
“YES. EXACTLY THAT. PERHAPS THERE ARE MORE. BUT I COULDN'T THINK OF IT. I DIDN'T HAVE A GUN. AND TWO AGAINST ONE IS UNFAIR, OR?” Thassalin hobbled to Kayel and patted him on the head. “THANK YOU, LITTLE ONE. YOU REMIND ME OF MY OLD FRIEND ARKADIN. JUST NOT SO MURDEROUS AND NOT SO ABLE TO KILL WHOLE UNIVERSES.”
“Umm… thanks… I think…”, shrugged Kayel with his shoulders. “So, are we done here then?”
Nyssi shrugged her shoulders. She grabbed her camera and took a few photos of the beasts that were now definitely dead. Then she drew her favorite weapon, the decorated Death God dagger, and began to saw off one of the beast's horns. Afterwards, she started on the second one. But as soon as Nyssi was finished, the beasts suddenly caught fire and in the blink of an eye turned into a pile of ash. The same thing happened to the horns that Nyssi had cut off.
„Well, that's both practical and impractical…“, sighed Nyssi. „But at least I have the photos, hopefully.“
